I‚Äôve been speaking in Tulsa, Oklahoma this weekend.¬† And I got a chance to get out to the Greenwood neighborhood home of Black Wall Street and the site of the Tulsa Massacre in 1921. ¬† [Thread] https://t.co/wXrBVVkqOs

There is a lot to take in ‚Äì memorials, murals, and the powerful interactive @GreenwoodRising museum. One of the rooms is a barber shop where you sit in a chair and listen to the stories of Tulsa at the time of the massacre. https://t.co/p87XwC0Wqg

This is an important part of history that not many of us know.¬† Tulsa was a segregated ‚Äúsundown town‚Äù with legal consequences if Black folks were on the other side of the railroad tracks after the sun went down.¬† But it was also the economic base of the Free Black community at‚Ä¶ https://t.co/HYlInKY4mZ https://t.co/kTb5GzsT3t

And the racial terror that fueled the massacre decimated the economy of Greenwood and took the lives of dozens (possibly hundreds) of people.¬† Information is still being discovered as mass graves are found and explored.¬† But Greenwood rose, and is still rising, from the ashes. https://t.co/KkFtfFAPmh

It was incredible to hear the stories of hope and resilience, joy and courage.¬† Here are a few more photos‚Ä¶ Please go visit if you are ever in Tulsa.¬† Oh, and at the end of the exhibit there are all sorts of action steps we can take to heal and repair the harm that was done in‚Ä¶ https://t.co/rRo04TqHkc https://t.co/353LA38Rjz

In one of the last rooms of the museum you can write your own personal commitment that is then displayed on the wall.¬† This was my commitment: ‚ÄúTell the truth about the past so we can build a better future.‚Äù https://t.co/n1whsmUE3r

I love being a dad. I don't take my roles in Elias's, Adeline's, and Ezra's stories for granted. I mean, I'm sure I do sometimes. I'm human after all. But I try to hold onto as many moments as I can. I fight to be present for them, to see and hear them. https://t.co/IfoaLenkaM
I work on myself; I process my trauma, my past, in effort to not repeat a broken cycle. I'm hardly perfect. But when I mess up, I apologize to my kids.

My hope is that I will parent them in such a way that I'll give them wings to fly rather than burdens to carry, that my words and my story will inspire them rather than become something from which they must recover.

There are so many emotions built into parenting--joys and fears and hopes and frustrations. I'm not one to give too much advice, especially when it comes to parenting. But if I've learned anything in the last 15 years of being a dad, it's this:
Humility is your friend. It's okay to tell your kids that you don't know the answer to their difficult questions. Follow "I don't know" with "let's learn about that together."

Parenting is not about "behavior management," it's about shining a bright light on the best path forward that you know, guiding them toward becoming the healthiest, happiest, and most capable adult humans that they can be.
It's about loving and caring for them in such a way that they will know how to love and care for someone else and also know how to receive somebody else's love and care.

Today is a difficult day for so many. Me included. Today reminds me of what I don't have. It reminds me of how much work I've had to do on myself in order to try and break the cycles that I experienced.

But it also reminds me of how far I've come and points me toward the work that I need to keep doing. While I'm not responsible for the trauma I experienced, I am responsible for what I do with it. I'm responsible for my healing.

I'm responsible for how my trauma effects other people. I'm responsible (along with their mama) for 3 lives, 3 stories, 3 beautiful passionate humans. For me, today is about them. Father's Day is about their stories, not mine...

*not*

Ideally, decision making at church HQ would occupy exactly zero thought processes our minds on a daily basis. The goal of the gospel is conversion, not "comprehensive awareness of decision-making at church headquarters." 4/

The happiest and most impactful church members are in deep alignment with Christ and His servants, and are allowing God to order their desires and priorities on a daily basis. Whatever is happening or not happening at church HQ today is not very relevant to that. 5/

Some thoughts on what sustaining means to me. üßµ
Sustaining doesn‚Äôt mean that we think church leaders are infallible. But it does mean that we give them the benefit of the doubt. 1/

Sustaining means we assume the best about their intentions, and we believe that they do in fact study issues in depth, and that they may have examined issues from angles that we have not considered. 2/ https://t.co/L2FEWmZ8pU
Sustaining doesn‚Äôt mean that we always agree with everything they say or do. But it does mean that before we disagree, we consider the best possible case for the validity of their position. 3/
It means that when they are unfairly criticized, we stand up for them, even at the risk of losing friends. 4/
It means that we stand with them in confronting external ideologies that undermine faith, and not the other way around. 5/
It means we resist the temptation to render their counsel meaningless and unrecognizeable in order to be able to claim we ‚Äúsustain.‚Äù 6/

It means that if everyone in the church were to adopt my sustaining stance, church leadership would feel supported even in difficult situations, even on difficult issues. That support would be completely evident to observers. 7/
Sustaining is not blind and it‚Äôs not fanaticism; it‚Äôs an informed commitment that recognizes God is operating through a specific system and order that is strengthened with our support. 8/
‚ÄúSustain unless it conflicts with my priors‚Äù and ‚ÄúSustain unless it causes really difficult feelings‚Äù are not sustaining. They are self-serving counterfeits.  9/
If I say I sustain a leader but my public comments are not what *they* would not recognize as support and I‚Äôm undermining their objectives, then let‚Äôs be honest- I‚Äôm not really sustaining. 10/

If sustaining is difficult sometimes, that doesn‚Äôt mean either you or church leadership are wrong or right, good or bad. It just means there is work to do, with patience and maybe a leap of faith. 11/

And it has a reciprocal element to it. We sustain because we know that at some point, there is a good chance we will need other people‚Äôs sustaining support, especially in instances where we might have disappointed others in some way. 12/

Sustaining is a challenging spiritual discipline- it‚Äôs not always easy. But I wholeheartedly recommend it, and Pres. Eyring‚Äôs talk linked below is great for further reading. 13/13

6/ But whether we like it or not, whether in real or virtual spaces we‚Äôre neighbors‚Äîand often family members. What would it look like for neighbors who have been locked in a destructive cycle of mutual animosity to begin to reestablish a relationship?

7/ Maybe it would look like just talking with one another, even about inconsequential things like the news. As John & I formulated the idea for the show, we had in mind all the people who are starving for civil discourse and gratified whenever and wherever they can find it.

8/ So why stop? Why pull out after only two episodes (which we have since taken down from YouTube)? It‚Äôs because I now realize after a tough couple weeks that I had focused so much on the positive potential of the show that I hadn‚Äôt fully counted the cost‚Äîto myself and others.

9/ I was frankly surprised by the visceral reactions to my announcement. I was heartened by the many positive responses and took seriously the many constructive criticisms of the project; it was definitely a work-in-progress.

10/ But I was stunned by the mean-spirited accusations and characterizations peddled by self-appointed guardians of orthodoxy and by people so brave and confident of their convictions that they post under the guise of anonymity.

11/ So many people were quick to issue public condemnations rather than reach out to me privately, even though my e-mail address is easy to find. 

Sticks and stones and all that‚Ä¶but it turns out that words do hurt, and often more people than just the intended target.

12/ Ultimately, however, I didn‚Äôt come to this decision because of my critics. I came to this decision because of my friends. People who know me, who trust me, who want my good, who shape me, who ask questions of me, who make me better.

13/ Those honest and private conversations, in the spirit of Matt. 18:15, led me to realize that more than a few people felt that when I turned to face Jana & especially John, I was turning my back on them. That in seeking to transform conflict I only exacerbated it.

14/ That‚Äôs not what I intended. It‚Äôs hard to be in the middle. I‚Äôm still learning how to build bridges between people who have been genuinely hurt and are so suspicious of the other side that seeing me engage (rather than fight) feels like betrayal or a loss of faith.

15/ Even after many years of heartfelt (and often heart-wrenching) conversations, I frankly underestimated the size of the divide between (some) Latter-day Saints and (some) post-/ex-Mormons and the ongoing pain that lives on both sides. It's fair to say I was a bit naive.

16/ I believe in making peace. With Pres. Nelson, I believe that peace-makers (not just peace-wishers) are badly needed today, and that members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints have a special responsibility in this sphere.

17/ But peace-making is tricky, risky, taxing work. Sometimes it‚Äôs hard to know when is the right time or what is the right forum. It‚Äôs possible to have sincerely good intent and still say or do something that pains or confuses people.

18/ I won't give up on making peace. I hope you won't either. Find someone who‚Äôs different from you and engage in an ongoing conversation with civility and generosity. Seeing someone else‚Äôs humanity and then treating them with dignity is one of the best gifts you can give them.

19/ I have so much love for John and Jana, and total respect for the way they came to this project with sincerity and a genuine desire to model healthier conversations. I wish you could have all listened in on some of the private chats we had along the way.
20/ Jana and John have been incredibly gracious in response to my decision to step away. If they choose to continue the conversation (stay tuned for further developments), I‚Äôll be cheering them on.

21/21 In the end, I apologize to anyone I've hurt, confused, or disappointed through either starting or stopping my involvement in this project. I'll keep trying to do and be better. In the meantime, let's all try our hardest to be good, kind, and generous to one another.

I woke up sad this morning, y'all. Yesterday I received 2 lengthy messages from parents of transgender kids. They reached out because they're worried about their kids. They're worried about their futures in light of so many states passing/trying to pass anti-trans laws.

While I can't fully understand the weight of all that they're feeling, that they're kids are feeling. As a parent who loves my kids and would fight like hell for their wellness and freedoms, my heart grieves and worries with them.

The Right (largely fueled by a hateful "Matt Walshesque" Christianity) have become so radicalized with their anti-trans (and also false) narratives that they are creating unsafe environments for kids. They're weaponizing the personhoods of children and inspiring/making harm.
They're waging their hate war under the false pretenses of "protecting children". They aren't protecting anything except their unhinged ideologies and egos.

But empathy is a superpower, y'all. We must fight back against the lies that a growing number of republicans not only believe but are using to emotionally fuel our political and spiritual landscapes. Walsh and his ilk have, in a short time, invented/promoted this hateful war.

It takes years to combat a lie, we know that. But we have to. We can't let their lies continue to put trans kids in harm's way. We must fight for the safety, wellness, personhoods of trans kids. We must support their rights/freedoms. They need our voices, our support, our votes.

And they need feel our love. To know that they aren't alone. That they belong. That they have advocates standing up for them and fighting on their behalf. 

May God keep every trans kid safe in these uncertain times.
